<p><b>Note 1:</b> The AFGC project will terminate in Dec. 31, 2002. This
web page will not be updated after September 1, 2002. However, the web
site will remain accessible from <a href= "/">TAIR</a>, The Arabidopsis Information Resource. 

<p><b>Note 2:</b> The T-DNA knockout component of the AFGC project will
continue as an independent project entitled <a href="http://www.biotech.wisc.edu/Arabidopsis/">"The End Game for Reverse Genetics in Arabidopsis: Isolation of a Knockout for Every Gene"</a> (PIs: M. Sussman and R. Amasino, University of Wisconsin). See additional information at the KNOCKOUTS page.

<p><b>Note 3:</b> A <a href="http://www.bch.msu.edu/pamgreen/PS_project/front.html">Plant-Specific Genes website</a>, in which information about
plant-specific genes is documented (e.g., expression profiles,
availability of T-DNA insertions lines, homologues in other plants), will
continue beyond the end of the AFGC project. See the PLANT-SPECIFIC GENES
page under the AFGC PROJECT tab above for additional information.  

<p><b>Note 4:</b>&nbsp;The GARNET group will be offering a public microarray service in the near future. Application forms for their service can be found at the following URL - <a href="http://www.york.ac.uk/res/garnet/application.htm">GARNET application form</a> <br></font><p> 
<p>The Arabidopsis Functional Genomics Consortium (AFGC) is an <a
href="http://www.nsf.gov"> NSF-</a>funded collaboration to understand gene
function in Arabidopsis by integrating two approaches: Microarray
Expression Analysis and T-DNA Gene Knockouts. The project scientists had a focus on understanding plant-specific genes utilizing these two technologies.

 
<p><li> Information about the AFGC project and the Plant-Specific Genes can be found via the AFGC PROJECT tab above.
	
<p><li>	Information about the Microarray component including various User Guides, Tools, a listing of experiments performed, and protocols can be reached via the MICROARRAY tab above. The AFGC microarray data, along with various data filtering and data analysis tools, are available from the Stanford Microarray Database (SMD, see SMD icon above).

<p><li>	Information about the T-DNA Knockout component and a link to the University of Madison home page for the Knockout project is at the KNOCKOUTS page (see tab above). 

<p><li>Links to other Microarray web sites and a listing of plant microarray and knockout papers can be found via the RESOURCES tab above. 
	
